body:
When trying to use `#[derive(Debug)]` in a structure whose inner elements use an associated type, it does not correctly take into account their required predicate. I'm not sure whether this is intended or not.

```rust

trait Bar {
    type Inner;
}
impl Bar for () {
    type Inner = u32;
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct Functional<T: Bar> {
    value: T::Inner
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct Broken<T: Bar> {
    value: Baz<T>
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct Baz<T: Bar> {
    value: T::Inner
}


fn main() {
    println!("{:?}", Functional::<()> { value: 0 });
    println!("{:?}", Broken::<()> { value: Baz { value: 0 } })
    
}
```

([Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=66960bceb9b7dc3b9e92aad27d23589b))

Errors:

```
   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0277]: `<T as Bar>::Inner` doesn't implement `Debug`
  --> src/main.rs:16:5
   |
16 |     value: Baz<T>
   |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^ `<T as Bar>::Inner` cannot be formatted using `{:?}` because it doesn't implement `Debug`
   |
   = help: the trait `Debug` is not implemented for `<T as Bar>::Inner`
   = note: required because of the requirements on the impl of `Debug` for `Baz<T>`
   = note: required because of the requirements on the impl of `Debug` for `&Baz<T>`
   = note: required for the cast to the object type `dyn Debug`
